metadata.name: tr4ns4ctions #61
metadata.description:
Tr4ns4ctions is a series of real-time animations that use pixels to create an abstraction of the movement of values. The pixels are constantly rearranging, being transferred from offer to taker, liquify, appear and disappear. They are forming endless compositions, sometimes intransparent or with strange spins.

The level of abstraction has been set to a 2x pixel size and the color palette of the NES with 12 different color modes. 16 pixel patterns serve as the fundamental building blocks and a simplex noise field determines the direction of movement.

click || space => pause/unpause

View all tr4ns4ctions at https://tr4ns4ctions.com

Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Grid Digger #47
metadata.description:
Grid Digger is a fairly simple algorithm. It draws a full grid of rectangles and then copies & pastes pieces of the canvas onto itself 200-1000 times, distorting the proportions of the pasted pieces each time.

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2024

metadata.name: The Tree Remembers #1
metadata.description:
In "The Tree Remembers", I wanted to create a feeling in the simplest way possible. I turned to two of nature's most familiar and captivating elements: a circle, representing the sun or moon, and a solitary tree. Together, they form a quiet dialogueâ€”timeless, still, yet full of presence.

The challenge was to build an atmosphere around these two elements, to let them interact and speak to each other without overcomplicating the composition. Simplicity guided every step: the form of the tree, the clean framing, and the deliberate avoidance of photorealism. Itâ€™s not about recreating a scene but about evoking the memory of oneâ€”a fleeting moment where light, sky, and nature align, and we pause to truly see it.

-------------------------

metadata.name: Soft Cell #40
metadata.description:
This work is an homage to relief printmaking. Other artists have explored the kinship between generative art and print using pen plotters and silkscreen. This work attempts to take the concept of a relief print and apply it to a digital canvas.

This art work is produced in layers. For each layer the printing surface or matrix is defined by one set of algorithms. Another set of algorithms then applies the "ink" (imperfectly!) to the matrix. For each layer in turn the matrix is then applied to the canvas.

Press [s] to save a png image of the work.

The work renders at an economical 800x800px. Any edge size may be specified by adding &sz=x to the URL. A print of about 6 inches by 6 inches is recommended, &sz=1800 at 300dpi.

Rust/JS/WASM
Polygon SDF algorithm adapted from Inigo Quilez.

metadata.name: Charcoal Landscapes #7
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of abstract landscapes using lines that are bounded to 8 directions. This limitation still allows for somewhat organic visuals and creates a visual language more akin to traditional drawing techniques.

Using a vector field with a noise function at different scales, I construct paths starting at random positions and moving to the neighbours cells pointed at by the vector field. Paths have a limitation of length and are bounded to the grid. I create tens of thousands of paths then render progressively on screen.

There are 10 parameters variations and 4 colors, 2 being rare and one very rare.

Original artwork by William Watkins Â· Lyon, 2021

metadata.description:
"Gribouillis" tends to reproduce the result of what you could draw without too much thinking on your sketchbook; an automatic drawing while listening to a call or podcast... Or something you would draw on the napkin of a restaurant without a strong focus...
Those kind of drawing that don't have a lot of meaning, but that, sometimes, give you find some comfort.

metadata.name: Pixel Management #2175
metadata.description:
#tezpole has demonstrated to us all the importance of effective Cable Management. Intrigued by this challenge, I've delved deep into the pixels of this issue. ðŸ™‚

Drawing inspiration from Rev Dan Cattâ€™s 'Tally!' and applying similar principles of Cable Management, I've assembled a fun and free OE project.

This project dynamically evolves with each iteration.Grid is determined by a random value calculated as follows: the lower bound starts at 3 and increases incrementally with every 100 iterations, while the upper bound starts at 4 and increases with every 30 iterations. In practical terms, as the iteration count increases, both the minimum and maximum possible number of cols&rows gradually increase.

3200x3200px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: Emotional Shell #180
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 72 Â· 54 Â· 40 Â· 30 Â· 24 Â· 20 every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted, and then drop one price tier.

---------

The feeling of being human â€“ with all of its intricate hopes, struggles, and fleeting emotions â€“ seems so unique that we assume artificial intelligence could never replicate our experience. And while we devise systems for solving unfathomably complex problems, generating algorithmic creativity, and unlocking regenerative biological possibilities, we simultaneously cling to the power and originality of emotional feeling â€“ believing it to be the irreplaceable source of what makes us human.

If the body is our shell for emotion and soul, can an artificial humanoid be another vessel for these thoughts and feelings â€“ for human essence itself? If our â€˜soulâ€™ is the last stand between us and the machines, what happens when the soul becomes transferable? That we may see answers to these questions looks more real every year, and is perhaps a little frightening. 

Emotional Shell uses introspective portraits of future selves to question what it means to be human, when the people around us are no longer human.

---------

metadata.name: <iframes> #497
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Ir/rational Beauty #149
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. www.tribute-hwf.com

"Since the classical age of Greece, the golden ratio has been well known as the most balanced and therefore most aesthetically perfect proportion. In fact, it is supposedly often found in the fine arts and architecture and it is certainly important in geometry. But where is the proof that it is really the most beautiful proportion?

"The computer is proving to be a useful tool in exact art theory. Works of computer art are produced with the help of programs that describe the logic of the construction and its relevant measures. By varying the parameters you can vary the shapes of objects, and on the basis of the reaction of the public you can determine the best option. So it is possible to find valid rules to design works of art.

"A statistical evaluation would be interesting. Please email me with your results for the optimal proportion."

I found it heartwarming that in 2011, Herbert W. Franke wrote the above, accompanied with a simple functional program on a Wolfram Demonstration page (https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/IsTheGoldenRatioReallyTheMostBeautifulProportion/) titled 'Is the Golden Ratio Really the Most Beautiful Proportion?' and invited people to submit their findings to him.

The main idea behind this project is ratios, a variety of them, used in a variety of ways, such as how a rectangle is repeatedly subdivided, or how it influences the aspect ratio of the piece, or how the colors in a palette are selected. These are represented in various styles, some of which are inspired by the aesthetic of Herbert W. Franke's diverse artworks, and his openness to experimentation with new technologies, such as plotter drawings, screens, screenprints, or 2D and 3D digital renderings.

This project, while not designed to be a formal statistical evaluation, is but my fun, colorful, and humble response to your inquiry, dear Herbert.

---

25% of primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke, with the goal of raising 20,000 Euros so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Frankeâ€™s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any money raised beyond this goal will be donated to the RÃ¼tgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

---

metadata.name: Ordered Chaos #41
metadata.description:
Ordered Chaos is a dynamic interplay of precision and distortion, where structure and movement converge to form a captivating visual symphony. The artwork unfolds as a mosaic of geometric grids, vibrant hues, and flowing deformations, creating a sense of controlled entropy.

Bold colorsâ€”emerald greens, electric blues, fiery reds, and glowing yellowsâ€”dominate the composition, their contrasts breathing life into each segment. Rigid, orderly grids anchor the piece, yet these are disrupted by undulating lines and warped forms, suggesting an unseen force bending structure into fluidity.

The composition balances tension and harmony. Some sections radiate stability, showcasing clean, linear patterns, while others twist and contort, evoking motion and transformation. These distortions ripple across the surface, connecting the fragmented forms into a single cohesive flowâ€”where chaos is not destruction but evolution.

Ordered Chaos reflects the duality of modern existence: a world shaped by digital precision and organic spontaneity. It invites viewers to immerse themselves in its patterns, to see order and disorder as two sides of the same whole, and to embrace the beauty that emerges when the two coexist in perfect tension.
